ut to 40Mpc\nand beyond. The halo and galaxy samples show a differing amplitude and range of\nconformity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 May 2017 07:05:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 6 Mar 2018 05:22:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-07-25"}
{"id":"1705.07583","submitter":"Wuchen Li","authors":"Shui-Nee Chow, Wuchen Li, Haomin Zhou","title":"A discrete Schrodinger equation via optimal transport on graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In 1966, Edward Nelson presented an interesting derivation of the Schrodinger\nequation using Brownian motion. Recently, this derivation is linked to the\ntheory of optimal transport, which shows that the Schrodinger equation is a\nHamiltonian system on the probability density manifold equipped with the\nWasserstein metric. In this paper, we consider similar matters on a finite\ngraph. By using discrete optimal transport and its corresponding Nelson's\napproach, we derive a discrete Schrodinger equation on a finite graph. The\nproposed system is quite different from the commonly referred discretized\nSchrodinger equations. It is a system of nonlinear ordinary differential\nequations (ODEs) with many desirable properties. Several numerical examples are\npresented to illustrate the properties.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 May 2017 07:06:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 25 Oct 2017 04:28:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-07"}
